Exercise 1 — Base template & DevTools 
The <!DOCTYPE html>, lang="en", and <meta charset="UTF-8"> are already in the 
head of index.html. Comments like <!-- Navigation -->, <!-- Main -->, <!-- Footer --> mark each section. Save the file, open it in Chrome, right-click → Inspect to see the DOM 
tree in Elements tab. 

Exercise 2 — Navigation 
The <nav> bar has anchor links pointing to #home, #events, #contact, which match the id 
attributes on each <section>. The Help link opens help.html in a new tab via 
target="_blank". 

Exercise 3 — Welcome banner 
#welcomeBanner has a blue background set through internal CSS. The special offer text uses 
an inline style directly on the <span> (red, bold). The .highlight class is reused wherever 
you want a quick visual emphasis. 

Exercise 4 — Image gallery 
A 2-row, 3-column table holds six <img> tags, each with alt, title, and a .imgBorder 
class for consistent styling. Captions sit under each image as plain text (you could swap these 
for <figcaption> if you restructure with <figure>). 

Exercise 5 — Registration form 
Covers text, email, date, select, and textarea inputs. placeholder, required, and 
autofocus are applied. On submit, showConfirmation() writes a message into the 
<output> element instead of reloading the page. 

Exercise 6 — Event handling 
● onblur on the phone field runs a regex check for 10 digits. 
● onchange on the dropdown displays the fee tied to the selected option via a data-fee 
attribute. 
● onclick on the submit button pops an alert confirmation. 
● ondblclick on any gallery image toggles its width between 150px and 300px to 
simulate "enlarging." 
● Keyup on the textarea updates a live character counter. 

Exercise 7 — Video 
The <video> element loads promo.mp4 with controls. oncanplay sets a "Video ready to 
play" message. window.onbeforeunload warns the user if they try to leave while the name 
field is filled in but the form hasn't been submitted. 

Exercise 8 — Storage 
savePreference() writes the selected event type to both localStorage and 
sessionStorage. On page load, window.onload checks localStorage and pre-selects 
the saved value. clearPreference() removes both. 

Exercise 9 — Geolocation 
Clicking "Find Nearby Events" calls getCurrentPosition() with enableHighAccuracy: 
true. Success shows coordinates; failure branches on PERMISSION_DENIED and TIMEOUT to 
show a friendly message instead of a raw error. 

Exercise 10 — Debugging 
Once you have this file running: 
● Right-click any element → Inspect Element, then edit CSS live in the Styles pane to test 
changes. 
● Open the Console tab — add a console.log() inside any of the JS functions above 
(e.g. inside countChars()) to watch values as you interact with the page. 
● In Chrome DevTools' Sources tab (or VS Code with the JavaScript Debugger), click a 
line number to set a breakpoint inside findLocation() or validatePhone(), then 
reload and step through with the debugger to watch variable values change. 
